<DOC><DOCNO> AP890307-0213 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 0624EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     03-07 0866</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0908</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Strike-crippled Eastern Airlines shut down nearly all operationsand idled 5,000 workers, saying it could not afford to maintain itsbusiness while pilots honored a 3-day-old Machinists walkout.   ``We can cannot run an airline with unpredictability,'' Easternspokesman Robin Matell said Monday in Miami. ``We cannot continue toinconvenience passengers. We cannot afford the steady financialdrain.''   Matell said Eastern would run only its most profitable routes,including its shuttle service between Washington, New York andBoston.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush won't push yet for a billbanning secondary picketing but is ready to move quickly if thestrike against Eastern Airlines spreads, a White House spokesmansaid.   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that as longas Eastern's striking members of the Machinists union refrain frompicketing other airlines or railways, ``we wouldn't find itnecessary to send up the legislation'' barring such secondary action.   The machinists said they would picket other airlines and railwaysbut called off the secondary actions after a New York court ruledother workers must not honor such picket lines.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's economy grew in February at theslowest rate in two years, according to a survey of purchasingexecutives.   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which tracksthe economy through its monthly survey of its members, said in areport Monday its Purchasing Managers Index fell slightly lastmonth, to 53.0 from 53.2.   The February level was the lowest for the index since February1987, when it was 52.6 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court refused to require thefederal government to crack down on interstate air polluters.   The court's action Monday involves a long-running controversybetween Northeastern states and the industrial Midwest overresponsibility for acid rain, which is caused by pollutants _primarily sulfur and nitrogen oxides _ from coal-burning powerplants and factories.   The justices Monday also enhanced the power of states to regulatenatural gas production, and, in a case stemming from Delta AirLines' takeover of Western Air Lines, refused to let Delta force theretirement of a group of flight engineers over age 60.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices of media companies soared asinvestors, dazzled by the $18 billion merger planned between TimeInc. and Warner Communications Inc., showed they were convinced thetrend toward the creation of media giants would continue.   Securities analysts said Monday they also expected to see moreconsolidations in the media business, although not of the magnitudeof the deal announced Saturday that will create Time Warner Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A buyout specialist offered to buy Ohio MattressCo., the world's largest bedding maker and producer of SealyPosturepedic and Stearns andamp; Foster mattresses, in a deal valuing thecompany at nearly $1 billion.   ``This is a great day for all our stockholders,'' said Ernest M.Wuliger, chairman and chief executive of Ohio Mattress, whichannounced Nov. 18 it had hired an investment banking firm to reviewa possible sale.   Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen said it was offering $25.50 a sharefor Ohio Mattress.</TEXT><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC nations produced about 19.4 millionbarrels of oil a day in February, less than in the previous monthbut still above their new production goal, according to newestimates.   The International Energy Agency in its Monthly Oil Market Reporton Monday estimated that production by the 13-nation Organization ofPetroleum Exporting Countries dipped last month from 20.2 millionbarrels a day in January.   The oil-producing nations agreed in November to slash outputstarting Jan. 1.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Authorities arrested two former senior officials ofJapan's largest corporation on suspicion of bribery in a spreadingstock scandal.   Prosecutors said Monday they arrested Hisashi Shinto, formerchairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., and a senior aide,Kozo Murata.   Investigators alleged the two officals were bribed with 10,000shares of unlisted stock that Murata was offered by Recruit Co., aninformation conglomerate.   The arrests followed the bribery indictments Saturday of fourother businessmen.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union said it needs more evidence thatcertain chemical compounds destroy the ozone layer before it joinsplans by the United States and other countries to ban them by theend of the century.   ``If we take a decision which is not well grounded, we caninterfere and destroy the economies of the developing countries,''said Vladimir Zhakarov, head of the Soviet delegation attending a120-nation conference on the ozone layer.   Western scientists agree that chlorofluorocarbons, commonly usedin refrigerators, aerosols and fast-food packaging, are graduallydepleting the ozone shield that protects the Earth from the sun'scancer-causing ultraviolet rays.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Entertainment and communications issues set the pace as the stockmarket staged a broad advance Monday. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials rose 20.53 points to 2,294.82.   The dollar rose against most foreign currencies.   Bond prices strengthened, helped by a rising dollar.   Platinum futures prices gained strongly; gold and silver futuresadvanced; copper futures declined; energy futures gained; grains andsoybeans were mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures weremixed.</TEXT></DOC>